title: E3D v5 and v6 40x40 Fan Duct remix (firmness and air flow)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I noticed two flaws in the original design:
It leaks air directly to the heating block and does not hold against the lower end of the heatsink allowing it to come loose and get askew.

I fixed both by "dragging" the airflow-divider towards the top (cutting the fan duct into slices and rearranging them in tinkercad).As I don't need the hole in the top I added a Version without it.

The Mesh seems a bit messy around the rejoint sections but it's on such a small scale that the slicer should ignore it (slic3r GCode looked fine...). I also checked that it's manifold and does not have any gaps.

edit 05.11.17:
Added fan duct for E3D v5 hotend (commonly referred to as "chinese clone") with bigger diameter and height.

the "..._v5_new.stl" schould fit right, the other one has slightly too small gaps for the fins of the heatsink in my case (used the exact dimension of 1.20mm thickness but my printer cant handle small gaps or holes too well...). The new one has 1.50mm gaps and should work fine for eveyone, but if it should be too loose try the other one.

The v5 one also has sloped edges to prevent it catching on warping edges at extreme overhangs. If you want the v5 one with these too just ask :)
Apart from that I changed two of the screw holes to be countered with a nut as 2 screws are enough to fasten it securely and now you can choose what type of screws to use. (tbh I just was too lazy to add that "pipe" behind the holes where these plastic screws can bite into...)

It looks even messier than the v6 one as I used tinkercad again and had to do pretty much rescaling and aligning, but te only effectively visible flaw is an indentation on the side... didn't bug me enough to fix it ;). Again printed fine in my case.

I used these drawings for getting the right dimensions when remixing:
https://wiki.e3d-online.com/images/7/7d/DRAWING-V5-SINK.jpg
https://wiki.e3d-online.com/images/0/0a/DRAWING-V6-175-SINK.png

btw I'm using both v5 and v6 right now and didn't have any problems like clogging etc.
see original design...

title: Sleeve for Lamy2000 fountain pen and mechanical pencil

description.text:
I wanted a sleeve for my Lamy2000 fountain pen and pencil together, so I designed one that could be printed using the spiral vase setting.
It's designed so that the end of the pen rests in the bottom of the holder rather than on the clip, so the cap won't be pulled off if it gets dropped in a bag. The pencil does hang from the clip to prevent breaking the lead.
I suppose this could be called a pocket protector.

They have a bit more clearance than I would like so I'll work on making a tighter version too.
Rev2 has a 0.5mm offset instead of 1mm, so it should be a snug fit. I haven't printed it yet.

Decided to derive a feeder upgrade for my ultimaker over the weekend using only stuff I already had lying around.
This is a basic derivative of the stock ultimaker feeder, but allowing a rollerblade bearing to be used to press the fibre against the hobbed bolt using a spring-loaded end block.
The vertices in the model were placed by hand (approximately) but the whole thing prints fine and seems to work all right (so far).

The whole thing was designed to allow me to use a rolleblade bearing as the "pressure roller" with which to press the fibre against the hobbed bolt. As these things are wider than 4mm, this required adapting a few more things and, while at it, I decided to implement the spring-loaded system seen on greg's extruder. printed at .2 slicing using PLA on an ultimaker.
The end-stop needs a bit of post-processing on the round bit, but the current version is easier to print. you'll also need the parts from the stock ultimaker feeder, one rollerblade bearing, two extra 3x30mm screws, two small springs and one 8mm bolt (or metal tubing) Due to limitations of my ability to print overhangs, You'll also have to saw or file off the bottom (printing platform side) of the "hooks" so that they are flush with the recessed "bridge". Then the whole thing can hook into the ultimaker without problems. It fits together only one way, you should be able to figure it out :-) once I've tested this thing for a few weeks I'll try to improve it a bit more (if I find the time)... edit:
-the parts have been rescaled to the right size. Now you can do a 1:1 print.
-the vertices have been positioned more accurately now.

title: Knuckle H-quad with walls for 10mm booms

description.text:
This project is inspired by Flitetests Knuckle H-quad.
( http://flitetest.com/articles/knuckle-h-quad )
that tophe75 made pritable
( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:163794 ) It is essential to get the booms perpendicular when building an H-quad. Since my printer is a lot more exact than me I wanted to use it's prowess to help me get it right. Thus the knucke-walls was born. The walls holds the 10mm booms in place making assembly easy. There is 1mm gap between the two halfs if you want to wick in some glue instead of using the holes with screws. Simple print out 8 angles and 2 hubs and you can start building. On the pictures you see me using the power distribution hub, battery/reciver bridge v2 and the ESC holder. (Also the crappy landing gears but they are to weak. Broke 3/4 in second landing. They will get an update!) I think I've manage to keep the simplicity of the Flitetest knuckle H-quad kit and even add a bit to it. Motor: http://hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/__18967__D2822_17_Brushless_Outrunner_1100kv.html (Not to happy with these though)

comments.text: An X525 frame is a standard "X" shaped quadcopter with 13mm square tubes for arms, and with the propellers 525mm apart.  When I say 135 degrees, I mean a shape like an arrow "/|".  If you put one of these near the end of each arm (near the motors) you could connect the ends of each arm to the adjacent arms.  The result would be a square frame connecting the arms together near the ends, which would create a really strong assembly.  Also, if you moved these same  brackets nearer to the center of the quadcopter, you could put one or two short cross-members between the arms - a wonderful place to hang a gimbal or a camera. A combination of little brackets that had exits on both sides, like a "T" and one that had two arms at 45 degrees, like a "Y"  and one that had arms at 135 degrees like " /|" would be really useful.  If you wanted to round out the list, you could make two more - one that had one arm at 45 degrees, like a one sided "Y" and one that had one arm at 135 degrees like "/| ".  If you made those for both 10mm and 13mm tubes, people could build an endless number of things.

description.text:
I have printed and used the -001 version. If using PETG, print with a wall thickness such that the walls will print fairly solid. The one that I printed was at .5mm thick walls. At this setting, it is almost vase mode. While PETG is fairly strong material, the thing did not withstand really bumpy roads. It cracked at the top, and was not stiff enough to retain the radio on the bottom, as it flexed too much. If you need to use this thing for an event, consider using some sort of strap to attach the radio to the bracket (rubber band, hook and loop strap, or maybe paracord).

Redesign considerations at this point: 1. Longer, to move the CG lower into the 'cup'. 2. Adding a cutout for the belt clip boss. 3. once the cutout for the clip boss is added, an anti-vibration spring will be added, similar to the one I put on the bike bracket for the ID51a. 4. because this radio is substantially heavier than any of my other radios, I may add a clip that goes over the front to add some support.

  • Note, do not print version -000. I printed one and will be making adjustments to the model. it fits the radio too tight due to the plastic flaring on the battery. I will be readjusting the slot location, and adding another slot for the after market battery (sundely), which has a shorter belt clip. *

After working events with my ID-51a, I was asked if I had a DMR radio, and could I work bicycle sweep for this event. This thing was rushed together, but should work. I marked it thing in progress, as I have not printed it yet. I think it should also work with the xpr-6550, as the batteries are interchangeable. This bracket only interfaces the battery and the attached belt clip. The clone battery will need another slot added, as it was shorter than the vertex one.

I will be printing in PETG as with the ID-51a bracket. It will be secured with zip ties and have strips of silicone rubber between it and the handlebars. When I get time, I will create a model of some tpu strips that lock into the bracket.

Yes, the radius is different on each leg. It is to compensate for the shape of my handle bars on my bike as you get farther from the center, they taper. I have a 2017 Specialized sirus carbon sport U.S. edition, with the radio mounted on the right side.

-001 - I added 1mm through the center to make it wider to miss the bump in the side of the battery. Moved the lower slot up, made it narrower, and added the second slot for the generic battery. I removed the -000 file. For 000, I printed it upside down. The droop from the clear span was not bad at all. I sliced in cura, printed in pronterface. No supports. Bed at 60, head at 240, on glass with aquanet as release agent.

description.text:
This is my design for a Jeep Door Storage Hanger for those times when you want to leave your jeep doors at home. Other commercial and DIY designs rely on hanging the doors using the window frame which can damage your window seals. The alternative metal hanging brackets are expensive for what you get so I figured I would try to print something and see how it performs. Other than your filament (I use PETG for strength), you should be able to get all the additional parts for less than $15.

NOTE: photos are of my prototype, I removed a screw mounting hole from the base plate and rounded off the hangers to allow doors to swing open and closed when hung. New photos soon.

The multi-part design should allow these to work with both TJ and JK models as well as to allow for the replacement of the hangers over time if they wear. Simply print (2) bases and (4) hangers for each pair of doors. Snap the hangers into the base (the funnel side of the base is the top, the triangle ends of the hangers are the bottom). Join each hanger to a base by inserting a 3/8 lag bolt fed down from the top and secured with a nut on the bottom. Once you have assembled both bases measure the appropriate distance between the hangers to match your jeep doors and mount the bases to a stud on your wall. I incorporated a funnel to help guide the door hinge pins into place.

Additional parts:

  • (4) 3/8 lag bolt, 4" or longer
  • (4) 3/8 nut
  • (4) mounting screws to attach to studs

The optional door catches allow you to latch the door against the wall if you wish to prevent the doors from swinging out. You'll need (2) 3/8-16 Square U Bolt Clamps (with no mount plate) and (4) 3/8 nuts and (2) 3/8 washers. Attach a nut and washer to each clamp leg and spin to the top of the thread. Feed the clamps through the holes on the catch plate and secure on the back with the remaining two nuts. Tighten down from the front nuts to secure the u bolt to the catch plate.
Parts:

  • (2) 3/8-16 Square U Bolt Clamps (with no mount plate)
  • (4) 3/8 nuts
  • (2) 3/8 washers.
  • (4) mounting screws to attach to studs

To mount the door catches, place a door in the installed door hanger. Secure the side of the mounted U Bolt Clamp into a door latch, then swing the door shut toward the wall, marking where the door catch plate should be mounted. Use the diagonal slots to mount the plate (preferably to a stud). You can flip the plate 180 degrees if your stud is to the left or right. The slots should allow you to fine adjust the latch position if needed.

This is the USS Enterprise from Star Trek TOS (The Old Series). Created in Mesh Fusion using plan and elevation diagrams found online.

The model provided is 100mm long. I found it very challenging to print as a single piece because it's very long and spindly. I printed it at 100mm nose down so that the nacelles were built growing upwards. This worked but had the problem of putting support structures towards the front of the model. The small one is in the image in front of my whiteboard.  
I was able to print it at 175mm by angling it 45 degrees nose upwards along the diagonal of the Afinia's roughly cubical print volume. This requires the rafts for the ends of the nacelles to be firmly attached so the nacelle bodies can grow at 45 degrees. Once they meet the struts, which grow out more sharply than 45 degrees, they are quite stable. The larger one I'm holding like Apollo in "Who Mourns for Adonis?"

title: Freezer 7 Pro CPU Cooler Fan Mount Replacement

description.text: I was refurbishing an old Core 2 Duo system as a server, and didn't want to buy a whole new heatsink just to replace the fan. This goes on in place of the Freezer 7 Pro fan shroud with a standard 80mm fan attached to it with some rubber grommets (could be adjusted to use screws fairly easily). I'm sure the airflow isn't as good as the standard shroud (less air coming in from the sides and helping to cool the motherboard and memory), but hey, at least it's active cooling!

Notes:

I printed with PLA, which isn't ideal but seems to be okay for now (if the computer gets hot enough to start melting PLA, it's got bigger problems). ABS would be preferable, but I have a hard time getting things to print in ABS without warping.

There are four variables at the top of the scad file that can be tweaked:

  • 'res' controls the circle tessellation.
  • 'xy_wall' should be the width of your nozzle (mine is 0.5mm).
  • 'z_layer' should be your z resolution (I used 0.15mm).
  • 'clip_overhang' can be adjusted to make the clip longer or shorter (a shorter clip will result in a stronger grab, but will tend to flex the base more and create gaps under the fan).

The 'build_mode' variable must be changed to "base" to render the mount for export, and "clip" to render the clip for export. You will need to print two of the clips.

After printing you will need to clean the bridging support out of the grommet holes.

Oh, and I had to cut the ends off the rubber grommets on the inside of the shroud after I'd mounted the fan in order to make it fit on the heatsink.

description.text:
Se trata de un simple dispositivo insiprado en el Big Mack, pero a bajo costo y facil ensamblado (Inspirado en http://www.redmundoingenio.com/component/hikashop/producto/18-big-mack-comunicador?Itemid=109 ) destinado a servir como herramienta para múltiples programas que requieran algún tipo de tecnología asistiva en lo referente a la comunicación.

Pueden verlo funcionar aquí: https://www.facebook.com/hipatetik/videos/10213034003698114/

El dispositivo en sí consta de un módulo ISD1820 adaptado para ser utilizado con pulsadores adicionales, y comandado externamente (jacks de audio de 3.5). La versión actual está pensada para ser usada con el módulo de la foto (disponible a muy bajo costo en Aliexpress), pero puede adaptarse para ser usado con otras versiones. Por defecto, el módulo graba hasta 10 segundos, pero cambiando la resistencia que forma parte del oscilador del mismo(R4, 100K por 200K), es posible llegar a 20segundos, aunque a menor calidad. Como elementos adicionales se requieren:
Portapilas AAA (dos pilas) AR$15
Led indicador 5mm AR$1
Cable(scrap) $0
Pulsadores normal abierto $scrap
2 Jacks de 3.5mm para panel
(viene con el modulo) Parlante de 8ohm 40mm diámetro (suele venderse junto con el módulo).
Tornillos M3 con tuercas x2
Tornillos para roscar pequeños (2mm aprox)

El módulo puede conseguirse en valores entre los $150 a $220 pesos argentinos a la fecha actual (10/2017). O bien adquirirse en Aliexpress por menos de dos dólares la unidad.

Herramientas necesarias: soldador, estaño, chupa estaño, destornilladores.

The device itself consists of an ISD1820 voice recorder module adapted to be used with additional pushbuttons, and externally controlled (3.5 audio jacks). The current version is intended to be used with the photo module (available at very low cost on Aliexpress), but can be adapted to be used with other versions. Changing R4 (default 100K, 10sec) you can get more time of recording (maximum of 20s, with a 200K resistor). As additional elements are required:

title: ANET A8 Back Brace (rear Y axis)

description.text:
Important accuracy is fairly critical for prints this size, and if you have existing problems with belt tension or damage to the belt, your accuracy might be off. Unless you changed something, you ought to be using stock X/Y calibration.

A small adjustment to the source part, I added in the 2nd support for the motor. This is important, it provides support for the rotational moment and helps to reduce the strain on the main mounting which I was worried might twist over time.

I also added screw holes for the back acrylic (although the location was not quite right in my print - should be better now). Guessing that more support here probably won't hurt, and i was planning to tap and use long M3 bolts for more stiffness.

I also mitred the corners so the print fits more easily on the bed. This has the advantage of providing a small amount of latitude with the dimensions, but you still need to be within 1-2%

Holes in the base were intended to give more strength.Printed in 6.30, at 0.32mm layer height. No support needed (I increased the angle of the hex hole to improve printing, the slots should be OK at 45 degrees)

Unless you've modified your printer's drive-train, this print should simply confirm correct calibration. Any 'errors' here are most likely due to damage to the toothed-belt, different drive wheels or different steppers. It's also possible that your steppers are skipping, or the belys are jumping.

To check calibration of X and Y, this is as large as can be comfortably measured with a 6" vernier. X and Y at 140mm, with diagonals as well. Any error in X and Y ought to contribute 0.707 to the error in the diagonals (which ought to be equal for any cartesian print)

Ends are undercut to avoid problems with the first layer. This means that you ought to run to layer 6 or 8 even for a 'quick' test using this part (which is where the individual X and Y may come in handy for a post-adjustment test. The two are of course the same (except for the rather fine labeling)

Takes about 1:30 to print at 0.2 mm, depending on layer and wall settings.

Be sure to let it cool before removing for best accuracy. Also serves as a bed-leveling check prior to an important print.

Update: Added X and Y stand-alone (labeled). Rounded the corners slightly.

This is a basic collar stay that I designed in three minutes based on a challenge on /r/functionalprint. It fits in two 80-character-column lines, or three for better legibility. The dimensions are probably wrong, since I never wear shirts fancy enough to put a collar stay into. That's why I haven't uploaded an STL. Open it in OpenSCAD and size it according to the shirt you want to use it in, or measure a collar stay that you already have. Just don't just print it out and then blame me that it doesn't fit.

It's three hulled cylinders, it doesn't get much more simple than that. Add $fn=50; at the top of the file if you want it to look smoother.

Print them on a 3d printer, or don't. I literally could not care less.

The collarstay_long file is not a longer collar stay, it's a longer file. By two lines.
